In article <1993Mar27.174343.24352@cs.aukuni.ac.nz> pgut1@cs.aukuni.ac.nz (Peter Gutmann) writes:
>
>"Reasonably" is the operative word here.  Somewhere I've got a large table
>of results for one of these dice done by some guy who rolled hundreds or
>even thousands of values on one to see how random it really was.  It wasn't
>terribly random - it was too hard to get a 100-sided polygon perfectly
>regular.  In fact even normal dice can be doctored by filing the edges or
>weighting them (I've got several loaded d6 which always roll either high or
>low).  If an attacker can get hold of the dice you used they can reconstruct
>any statistical irregularities and use them as the basis for an attack on
>your random numbers.

Agreed. But if I'm *that* paranoid, I'll destroy my dice after
generating my RSA key pair. Of course, ``they'' could always have
messed with The Compleat Strategist's supply of dice in the first place.

>
>BTW in my random collection I've also got a d6 which is marked in powers of 2
>from 2 to 64 - no idea what it's used for though.
>

It's a "doubling" die for the american variant of backgammon. 

